
TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Process of Schema Emergence: Assimilation, Deconstruction, Unitization and the Plurality of Analogies
AU  - Bingham, Christopher B.
AU  - Kahl, Steven J.
Y1  - 2012/05/07
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2013/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2010.0723
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2010.0723
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 14
EP  - 34
VL  - 56
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Schemas are a central concept in strategy and organization theory. Yet, despite the importance of schemas, little is known about how they emerge. Our in-depth historical analysis of how groups in the life insurance industry developed their schema for the computer from 1945?1975 addresses this gap. We identify three key processes?assimilation, deconstruction, and unitization?that collectively explain and resolve an inherent tension related to schema emergence: how to make the unfamiliar familiar but conceptually distinct. We also find that each process relates to analogical transfer, but in a more pluralistic and dynamic way than the existing literature describes. Broadly, these findings have important implications for organizational change and managerial cognition.
AB  - Schemas are a central concept in strategy and organization theory. Yet, despite the importance of schemas, little is known about how they emerge. Our in-depth historical analysis of how groups in the life insurance industry developed their schema for the computer from 1945?1975 addresses this gap. We identify three key processes?assimilation, deconstruction, and unitization?that collectively explain and resolve an inherent tension related to schema emergence: how to make the unfamiliar familiar but conceptually distinct. We also find that each process relates to analogical transfer, but in a more pluralistic and dynamic way than the existing literature describes. Broadly, these findings have important implications for organizational change and managerial cognition.
